thought.text:
Good. `SetValuesAndLabels`:
1. Sets `Values` - the `Values` setter calls `CreateSubViews()` then `UpdateChecked()` — but at this point `Labels` is still null, so `CreateSubViews` returns early (Labels is null check)
2. Sets `Labels` - the `Labels` setter calls `CreateSubViews()` then `UpdateChecked()` — now Labels is set and Values is set, so CheckBoxes are created and the right one is checked

This is the same pattern used by `FlagSelector<TEnum>`. It ensures both explicit paths are invoked.

Now let me also check - does the `Values` setter properly handle the case where the `OptionSelector()` base constructor already set `Value = 0`? Let me check:

```csharp
// Values setter:
set
{
    field = value;
    // Ensure Value defaults to the first valid entry in Values if not already set
    if (Value is null && field?.Any () == true)
    {
        Value = field.First ();
    }
    CreateSubViews ();
    UpdateChecked ();
}
```

When `SetValuesAndLabels` sets `Values`, `Value` is already 0 (set by the base constructor). So `Value is null` is false, and the defaulting logic is skipped. Then `CreateSubViews()` runs - but Labels is still null, so it returns early. Then `UpdateChecked()` runs - no SubViews exist, nothing happens.

Then `Labels` is set. `Labels` setter: `CreateSubViews()` runs - now both Labels and Values are set, CheckBoxes are created. `UpdateChecked()` runs - checks the one with Value=0.

This is correct.

Now, there's one concern: `OptionSelector<TEnum>` overrides `Values` to prevent setting:
```csharp
public override IReadOnlyList<int>? Values { get => base.Values; set => throw new InvalidOperationException (...); }
```

But `SetValuesAndLabels` is defined in `SelectorBase` and calls the `Values` setter. Since `OptionSelector<TEnum>.Values` overrides the setter to throw, calling `SetValuesAndLabels<TEnum>()` from `OptionSelector<TEnum>` will THROW!

